  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a firm knowledge of Spanish SSCs in order to accurately
  transcribe spoken Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.324026Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29224-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a broad vocabulary to be successful at answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.324030Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29224-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to listen out for synonyms and distractors when answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.324035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26156-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Frida Kahlo was a Mexican painter known for her vivid self-portraits inspired by
  pain, identity, and Mexican culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.327957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26156-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns replace the person or thing that the action is done to when
  it is to me, for you, to them, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.327961Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26156-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns in Spanish are ‘me’, ‘te’, ‘le’ and ‘le', 'nos', 'os' and
  'les'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.327965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26156-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns can go before the conjugated verb or attach to the
  infinitive in two-verb constructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.327969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26127-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verb forms contain orthographic changes. These are spelling changes made to
  preserve or aid pronunciation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.332496Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26127-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some -er / -ir verbs with ‘g’ in the stem change to 'j' in the 1st person singular
  to preserve the soft [g] sound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.332500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26127-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Verbs ending in -uir gain a 'y' in persons 1,2,3 and 6 to aid pronunciation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.332504Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26154-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, to express a feeling, emotional reaction or opinion, you often use verbs
  of emotion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.336568Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26154-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs of emotion ('gustar', 'encantar', 'dar', 'molestar', etc.) are followed by an
  infinitive or the subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.336572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26154-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When verbs of emotion are followed by the conjunction 'que', use the
  subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.336576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26154-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use a verb of emotion + 'que' + subjunctive for reacting to someone else's action or
  situation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.336580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26167-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the present continuous, use the present tense of 'estar' followed by the
  present participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353280Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26167-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the imperfect continuous, use the imperfect tense of 'estar' followed by the
  present participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353285Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26167-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the present participle of -ar and -er/ir verbs, remove the infinitive ending
  and add -ando or -iendo."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26167-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs have spelling changes in the present participle e.g. 'construyendo',
  'leyendo', 'pidiendo'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26167-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29214-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Desde hace' means 'for' and it appears together with the present tense to say how
  long we've been doing something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29214-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Hace' means 'ago' and we use it with the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29214-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use the present tense of 'llevar' + time + present participle to say how long we
  have been doing something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29214-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.353315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29225-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a broad vocabulary to be successful at answering reading
