  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to carefully check verb endings and adjectival agreement when
  translating from English to Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29221-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You should answer role-play prompts with a short phrase or sentence. Do not add
  unnecessary detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360538Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29221-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a firm understanding of sound-spelling correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29221-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use the PALM acronym to structure photo descriptions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360546Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29221-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the conversation following the photo description, you should aim to develop
  answers using at least 3 verb clauses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26163-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The modal verbs 'querer', 'poder', 'deber' and 'tener que' are followed by an
  infinitive verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360685Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26163-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-symbol correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26163-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to spot tricky sounds and cognates, and mentally rehearse before
  reading aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26163-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to look out for synonyms and distractors when answering reading
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26197-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26197-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to carefully check verb endings and adjectival agreement when
  translating from English to Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26181-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can boost our word knowledge by making connections between words such as word
  families, synonyms, opposites, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26181-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To mean 'you' in an informal context, use 'tú'. In a formal context, use
  'usted'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26181-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is common to address unfamiliar people as 'usted', for example in commercial
  settings like a shop or restaurant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26181-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The plural form of 'usted' is 'ustedes'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26181-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Usted' and 'ustedes' respectively take the 3rd person singular and plural forms of
  the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29217-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the affirmative imperative to tell somebody to do something or to give
  instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29217-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For 'vosotros' commands, use -ad for -ar verbs, -ed for -er and -id for -ir verbs.
  This is the affirmative imperative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29217-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The final -d of reflexive plural imperative verbs is dropped and -os is added, e.g.
  '¡callaos!' - 'be quiet!' (you pl)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29217-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26182-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a firm knowledge of Spanish SSCs in order to accurately
  transcribe spoken Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26182-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a broad vocabulary to be successful at answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26182-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to listen out for synonyms and distractors when answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29208-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To conjugate the perfect tense, use the verb 'haber' + past participle."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29208-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form the past participle of regular -ar verbs, remove the -ar and add -ado."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29208-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the past participle of regular -er/ir verbs, remove the -er/ir and
  add -ido."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29208-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A well-developed conversation answer contains three verb clauses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26121-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used for descriptions, giving background information and
  ongoing events in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26121-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The preterite tense is used for completed events in the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26121-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We use the 3rd person singular and plural when we talk about a film."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26030-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Regular -ar verbs: 3rd person singular and plural, PAST preterite (-ó, -aron)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26030-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The sound [j] followed by any vowel sounds like 'jugar'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26030-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The sound [g] followed by a, o or u sounds like 'gol'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26151-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Grouping vocabulary thematically is an effective way to revise and retain words."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26151-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Tan ... como' means 'as ... as' in comparisons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26151-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form other comparatives in Spanish, use 'más' or 'menos' + adjective + 'que'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366507Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26151-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Lo' + adjective is used to talk about general or abstract ideas, e.g. 'the best
  thing' or 'the bad part'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366511Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26165-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate regular -ar verbs in the preterite tense, use the endings -é, -aste,
  -ó, -amos, -asteis, -aron."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.367310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26165-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate regular -er/-ir verbs in the preterite tense, use the endings -í,
  -iste, -ió, -imos, -isteis, -ieron."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.367317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26165-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate regular -ar verbs in the imperfect tense, use the endings -aba, -abas,
  -aba, -ábamos, -ábais, -aban."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.367321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26165-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate regular -er/-ir verbs in the imperfect tense, use the endings -ía,
  -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.367325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26165-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The only irregular verbs in the imperfect tense are 'ir' ('iba'), 'ser' ('era') and
  'ver' ('veía')."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.367329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26031-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say ‘his’, ‘her’ or ‘its’ before a singular or uncountable noun, both masculine
  and singular, we use ‘su’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.371868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26031-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Su’ and ‘sus’ mean ‘their’, referring to something that belongs to more than one
  person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.371872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26031-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Spanish doesn’t have a word for ‘do’ or ‘did’ in questions (auxiliary). Only the
  main verb is used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.371876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26048-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Nada' means 'nothing, anything', 'nadie' means 'nobody, anybody', and 'nunca' means
  'never'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26048-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When ‘nada’, ‘nadie’ and ‘nunca’ follow a verb, another negative such as ‘no’ must
  come before the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26048-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unlike English, double negative structures in Spanish are widely used in formal and
  informal language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26048-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate regular -ar verbs in Spanish, take off the infinitive ending and add
  the approriate verb ending."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29211-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish there are two verbs for 'to be'. Use 'estar' for location, state or mood
  and 'ser' for permanent traits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29211-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used to express how things were or used to be in the past, or
  to say what was happening."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29211-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Estar' is an irregular verb in many tenses, but it follows regular patterns in the
  imperfect tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29211-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In the imperfect tense, 'estar' is conjugated regularly using -ar verb endings."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.374844Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26065-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to convey a range of
  information."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.376877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26065-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The PALM acronym is a useful prompt to include a range of information when
  describing photos."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.376881Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26065-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to use full sentences
  with verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.376885Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26065-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can form answers to questions in Spanish by converting 2nd person language into
  1st person language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.376889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26119-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Question words are essential when asking and understanding questions about social
  media."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.381874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26119-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to develop answers to questions by using a variety of opinions,
  justifications and contrasting ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.381878Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28168-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The subjunctive mood expresses actions which are uncertain, wished for, or that have
  not yet happened."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28168-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The subjunctive forms of ‘ser’ and ‘tener’ are: 'sea', 'seas', 'sea'; 'tenga',
  'tengas', 'tenga'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28168-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When forming a 'when/if' sentence with 'cuando' the structure is generally 'cuando'
  + subjunctive + inflectional future."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394293Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28168-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In conversation, develop answers by adding opinions, reasons, examples/extra details
  and different time frames."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26152-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When approaching extended writing tasks, dividing each bullet point into at least
  two paragraphs can be helpful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.395677Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26152-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.395680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26152-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You can apply BORDER to every paragraph in your writing."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.395684Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26150-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The verbs 'ser' and 'ir' have the same preterite tense conjugations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399464Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26150-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The preterite tense forms of 'ser' and 'ir' are 'fui', 'fuiste', 'fue', 'fuimos',
  'fuisteis' and 'fueron'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26150-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The preterite tense of 'ser' can be used to describe completed events or situations
  in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26150-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """World Book Day (April 23rd) marks Cervantes' and Shakespeare's deaths. Many Spanish
  cities celebrate with book fairs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399478Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26150-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Catalonia, Sant Jordi coincides with World Book Day. People give a book and a
  flower as a symbol of love and culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26166-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-symbol correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26166-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to spot tricky sounds and cognates, and mentally rehearse before
  reading aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26166-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a broad vocabulary to be successful at answering reading
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26166-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to look out for synonyms and distractors when answering reading
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26134-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The relative pronoun 'lo que' means 'what' or 'the thing that' and refers to a
  general idea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.402657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26134-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The relative pronoun 'lo que' can be used to extend written answers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.402661Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26134-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating into English, it is important to identify who or what the relative
  pronoun refers to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.402665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26134-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating into English, it is important to consider the position of the
  prepositions within a sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.402673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26134-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the acronym BORDER to structure, develop and enhance your response with key
  content and varied language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.402677Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26054-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Es means 'she, he, it is' and 'era' means 'I, she, he, it was'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26054-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The pronouns 'yo', 'él' and 'ella' make the meaning of 'era' clear."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405253Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26054-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Es' and 'era' often appear before adjective and an infinitive when describing a
  situation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405257Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26054-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Eres' means 'you are' and 'eras' means 'you were' or 'you used to be'"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405262Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26092-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When completing listening comprehension questions, it is important to listen to the
  whole text before answering."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26092-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a listening comprehension, the information relevant to the answer may appear at
  any point in the text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406530Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26092-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Be aware that synonyms and phrases related to the question terms are often used in
  listening comprehension texts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406535Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26092-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, 'r' in the middle or at the end of a word is pronounced as in
  'pero'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26092-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, 'r' at the beginning of a word and 'rr' are pronounced as in
  'perro'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26110-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, [r] is pronounced differently depending on its position within a
  word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406547Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26110-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, accents indicate where the stress should fall if this doesn't follow
  standard rules."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26110-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The inflectional future expresses what will happen and the conditional expresses
  what would happen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406555Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26110-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ir a + infinitive' is a 2-verb structure used to express what is going to
  happen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26110-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406563Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28171-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The subjunctive expresses uncertainty, wishes, emotions or future possibilities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406666Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28171-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'cuando' + indicative if the action is regular or certain, and 'cuando' +
  subjunctive if the action is uncertain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406672Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28171-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After statements of fact or certainty use the indicative; after subjective points of
  view, use the subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406677Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28171-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wishing verbs ('querer', 'esperar', 'desear', 'preferir', 'necesitar') are followed
  by an infinitive or the subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28171-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use a verb of wishing + 'que' + subjunctive when you want someone else to do
  something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26095-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Working with a partner is a useful way to practise vocabulary; repeat tricky words
  several times to remember them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.421926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26095-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Fiestas del pueblo' are festivals in a town or village, typically in summer, where
  there is music, food, and tradition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.421930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26095-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regular -er and -ir verbs in the 3rd person singular and plural preterite have the
  endings -ió (s/he) and -ieron (they)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.421934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26095-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Questions are expressed through intonation;  there is no word for 'do' or 'did'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.421938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26023-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[l] and [ll] do not sound the same in Spanish. [ll] is pronounced as in ‘calle’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423859Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26023-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Classifying words by parts of speech is one useful strategy for consolidating
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26023-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hacer is an irregular verb. The singular forms are ‘hago’, I do/make, ‘haces’, you
  do/make, ‘hace’, she, he does/makes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26023-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use ‘hace’ to talk about the weather: hace calor/frío/etc. This translates as ‘it
  is’ in English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26023-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Check verbs, nouns and adjectives, word order, little words and idiomacy when
  translating into Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26109-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, adjectives usually follow the nouns they describe to communicate a
  literal, objective description."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26109-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjective position in Spanish can vary. Adjectives before a noun can communicate a
  figurative, subjective description."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26109-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The conditional is a verb form used to express what would happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26109-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate singular forms of the conditional, add -ía, -ías, -ía to the
  infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26109-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Habría', 'haría', 'podría', 'pondría' and 'tendría' are common irregular
  conditional verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26126-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The suffix -able is used to form adjectives and it is typically added to -ar
  verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26126-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns replace the person or thing that the action is done to,
  when it is to me, for you, to them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26126-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Indirect object pronouns in Spanish are ‘me’, ‘te’, ‘le’ and ‘les’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26126-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns precede the verb in 1-verb constructions, e.g. ‘me da la
  pelota’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425857Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26157-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Pablo Picasso was a Spanish artist and key 20th-century figure, known for
  co-pioneering the Cubist movement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26157-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Guernica' is Picasso's famous anti-war painting, showing the horror of the Spanish
  Civil War bombing in 1937."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425866Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26157-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Alguno/a' and 'algunos/as' mean 'some', 'any' or 'a', 'an' and are used in
  affirmative sentences and questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26157-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ninguno' and 'ninguna' mean 'none', 'no-one', 'not a single one'; they are always
  used in the singular form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26157-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indefinite adjectives and indefinite pronouns are identical apart from the masculine
  singular form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.425879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26107-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The PALM acronym is a useful tool to include a range of information when describing
  photos."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.426500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26107-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to plan extended answers to talk
  for a prolonged period of time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.426506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26107-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When responding to conversation questions in Spanish, it is important to develop
  answers with 2-3 clauses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.426510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26049-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs with ‘e’ in the stem (e.g. pensar) change to ‘ie’ for persons 1, 2, 3 and
  6."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427462Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26049-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs with ‘o’ in the stem (e.g. volver) change to ‘ue’ for persons 1, 2, 3 and
  6."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427466Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26049-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Ninguna' means 'no, not … any' (before a feminine singular noun)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26049-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Ningún' means 'no, not … any' (before a masculine singular noun)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26049-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Ni’ (neither, nor), ‘ya no’ (not any more) and ‘sino’ (but) are useful negatives in
  Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427478Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26074-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A strong knowledge of high frequency vocabulary is key to unlocking effective
  listening comprehension."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26074-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Prediction involves anticipating what the answers might be by generating relevant
  words in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26074-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Recognising synonyms often involves identifying specific examples of a more general
  category, e.g. 'manzana' - 'fruta'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26074-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Identifying and avoiding distractors is key to ensuring we don’t jump to the wrong
  conclusions during listening tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26074-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In a role-play scenario, you have to ask  as well as answer questions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26019-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The modal verbs 'querer', 'poder', 'deber' and 'tener que' are followed by an
  infinitive verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427735Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26019-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 2-verb structures, direct object pronouns can go before the conjugated verb and
  attached to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26019-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When using verbs in the negative form with direct object pronouns, the 'no' needs to
  go before the object pronoun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26019-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[z] sounds like 'zapato' and [co] sounds like 'coche'. Pay attention to these two
  key sounds in words like 'conozco'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26019-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The translation for 'saber’ + infinitive is ‘can’, meaning ‘to know how to’ do
  something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27618-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Like ‘ir’, ‘ver’ is irregular in the imperfect tense."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27618-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘veía’, ‘veías’ and ‘veía’ are the 1st, 2nd and 3rd person singular forms of ‘ver’
  in the imperfect tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429626Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27618-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used to talk about something that used to happen repeatedly
  in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27618-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect endings of regular -er and -ir verbs are -ía, -ías, -íamos, -íais and
  -ían."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27618-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The preterite tense is used to talk about something completed in the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429641Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26082-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to revisit previously learnt words regularly to store them in your
  long-term memory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26082-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Stem-changing verbs have a change in the stem for some grammatical persons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26082-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs with 'e' in the stem (e.g. pensar) change to 'ie' for persons 1, 2, 3 and
  6 in the simple present."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26082-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs with 'o' in the stem (e.g. encontrar, poder) change to 'ue' for persons
  1, 2, 3 and 6 in the simple present."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26104-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to revisit vocabulary frequently to store it in your long-term
  memory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429664Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26104-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """BORDER is a useful acronym to respond fully and accurately to bullet-point writing
  prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26104-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To develop written answers, you can add relevant information about another person or
  incorporate another time frame."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429675Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26104-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can extend written answers by adding an infinitive phrase, a relative clause, or
  a contrasting clause."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.429681Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26131-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The perfect tense is used to express what has happened, e.g. 'I have listened', 'I
  have bought."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.430964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26131-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, the perfect tense is formed from the auxiliary verb 'haber' and the past
  participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.430968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26131-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to read the questions before the audio and listen the whole text
  before answering listening questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.430972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26075-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The perfect tense is used to express what has happened."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26075-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate singular forms of the perfect tense, use 'he', 'has' or 'ha' (from
  'haber') + past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431007Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26075-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form the past participle of regular -ar verbs, remove the -ar and add -ado."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431011Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26075-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Common irregular past participles are 'escrito' (written), 'hecho' (done, made),
  'visto' (seen) and 'puesto' (put)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26114-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of -er verbs in the simple present, remove the -er and add
  -emos, -éis, -en."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26114-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of -ir verbs in the simple present, remove the -ir and add
  -imos, -ís, -en."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26114-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of -er/-ir verbs in the preterite, remove the -er/-ir and
  add -imos, -isteis, -ieron."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26103-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-spelling correspondences to
  accurately read aloud Spanish texts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433775Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26103-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is a good idea to mentally rehearse a text before reading it aloud."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433779Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26103-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The inflectional future expresses what 'will' happen and 'voy a + infinitive'
  expresses what is 'going to' happen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26103-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plural conjugations of the inflectional future are formed by adding the endings
  -emos, -éis or -án to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26103-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Saber', 'querer', 'venir', 'decir', 'salir' have irregular future stems: 'sabr-',
  'querr-', 'vendr-', 'dir-', 'saldr-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26064-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indefinite adjectives refer to non-specific or undefined qualities, people or
  things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26064-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form comparatives in Spanish, use más or menos + adjective + que."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26064-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say something is better or worse than something else, use 'mejor que' or 'peor
  que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26064-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form superlatives in Spanish, use noun + más or menos + adjective."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26064-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When using comparative and superlative structures, the adjective must agree with the
  preceding noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.433811Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28167-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The inflectional future tense is used to express what will happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.439066Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28167-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Singular conjugations of the inflectional future are formed by adding the endings
  -é, -ás or -á to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.439070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28167-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verbs 'tener', 'hacer' and 'poder' have irregular stems in the future tense:
  'tendr-', 'har-' and 'podr-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.439074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28167-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The subjunctive is a verb form that indicates uncertainty, wishing or refers to
  actions that have not yet happened."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.439080Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28167-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Cuando' is a conjunction that is followed by a subjunctive verb when the action
  hasn't yet occurred or is uncertain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.439085Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26124-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Aquel' and 'aquella' both mean 'that' before a singular or uncountable noun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26124-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Aquello' means 'that (thing)' for something that is unspecified."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26124-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Aquello' never appears before a noun and often appears before the relative pronoun
  'que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26124-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs like 'poner' add 'g' to the end of the stem in the first person singular of
  the present tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26124-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs like 'conocer' add 'z' before the final 'c' of the stem in the first person
  singular of the present tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26145-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Spanish is the official language in 21 countries across 3 different continents."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26145-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Spanish is spoken differently across various countries, with notable linguistic
  variations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587458Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26145-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Latin America, 'ustedes' is used for both formal and informal situations instead
  of 'vosotros'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587462Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26145-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ending for 2nd person singular for -ar verbs in the present tense is -as and
  -áis for the 2nd person plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26070-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A small number of verbs are irregular in the inflectional future and have irregular
  future stems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26070-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "‘Decir’, ‘poner’ and 'salir' have irregular stems in the inflectional future."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26070-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the inflectional future, the endings are added to the infinitive and they are the
  same for -ar, -er and -ir verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26070-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The endings for the singular persons of the inflectional future are: -é (I), -ás
  (you) and -á (she, he, it)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26070-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The endings for the plural persons of the inflectional future are: -emos (we), -éis
  (you all) and -án (they)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26069-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the inflectional future tense of regular verbs in the singular, add the
  endings -é, -ás, -á to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26069-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb stems of 'saber', 'querer' and 'venir' in the inflectional future are
  'sabr-', 'querr-' and 'vendr-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587533Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26069-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the inflectional future tense of regular verbs in the plural, add -emos,
  -éis, -án to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587541Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26069-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form comparatives in Spanish, use 'más' or 'menos' + adjective + 'que'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587546Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26069-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Más de' means 'more than' when followed by a number."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26013-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make a noun plural, add -s if it ends in a vowel, and -es if it ends in a
  consonant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26013-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When we make a masculine noun plural, the indefinite article 'un' changes to
  'unos'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591767Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26013-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When we make a feminine noun plural, the indefinite article 'una' changes to
  'unas'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26013-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regular -er/-ir verbs: 1st, 2nd, 3rd person singular PAST preterite (-í, iste &
  -ió)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26034-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Knowing a word means you can understand it in listening and reading but also use it
  in speaking and writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26034-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Formation of plural nouns rule 4: when a word ends in -ión, add -es and remove the
  accent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26034-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cognates may look very similar to English but sound quite different so attention
  must be paid to pronunciation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26034-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """1st person singular of verbs with irregular preterite stems: dije, estuve, pude,
  puse, quise, supe, traje and vine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26034-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The singular persons of irregular verbs ‘ir’ and ‘hacer’ are: ‘fui’, ‘fuiste’,
  ‘fue’, ‘hice’, ‘hiciste’ and ‘hizo’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26011-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In questions, to say 'a', 'an' or ‘any’ before masc. sing. nouns use ‘algún’ and
  'algunos' before masc. pl. nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26011-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In questions, to say 'a', 'an' or ‘any’ before fem. sing. nouns use ‘alguna’ and
  'algunas' before fem. pl nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26011-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some adjectives can go before the noun. These are called 'prenominal
  adjectives'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591811Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26011-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Prenominal adjectives 'primero', 'tercero', 'bueno', 'malo' and 'alguno' come before
  the noun and lose the -o ending."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591815Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26011-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs ending in '-car', 'gar' or '-zar' have a spelling change in 1st person
  singular in the preterite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.591819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26090-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the affirmative imperative to tell somebody to do something or to give
  instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26090-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to somebody familiar to you ('tú') with the affirmative imperative of
  an -ar verb, use the ending -a."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593873Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26090-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to somebody familiar to you with the affirmative imperative of an -er
  or -ir verb, use the ending -e."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26090-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verbs 'hacer', 'decir', 'poner' and 'salir' are irregular in the imperative,
  becoming 'haz', 'di', 'pon' and 'sal'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593884Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26144-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Andalusia (Andalucía in Spanish) is a region in southern Spain known for its rich
  history and culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593888Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26144-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To express opinions and make suggestions, we can use some impersonal verbs in the
  3rd person singular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26144-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Examples of impersonal uses of verbs are ‘basta (con)’, ‘falta’, ‘hace falta’,
  ‘parece’ and ‘vale la pena’ ."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26144-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "These impersonal verbs are used without a subject and followed by an infinitive."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593901Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26130-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the affirmative imperative to tell somebody to do something or to give
  instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26130-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to people familiar to you ('vosotros') with the affirmative imperative
  of an -ar verb, use the ending -ad."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26130-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to people familiar to you ('vosotros') with the affirmative imperative
  of an -er verb, use the ending -ed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593913Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26130-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to people familiar to you ('vosotros') with the affirmative imperative
  of an -ir verb, use the ending -id."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26130-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The final -d of reflexive plural imperative verbs is dropped and -os is added, e.g.
  '¡callaos!' - 'be quiet!' (you pl)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.593921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26055-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The demonstrative pronouns 'esto' and 'eso' mean 'this' and 'that'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596047Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26055-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unlike 'este', 'esta', 'ese' and 'esa', 'esto' and 'eso' cannot appear before a
  noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26055-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Eramos' means 'we were', 'erais' means 'you all were' and 'eran' means
  'they were'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596055Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26055-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Cue' is pronounced as in 'cuerpo', 'cua' as in 'cuatro' and 'cui' as in
  'cuidar'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26133-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'El que', 'la que', 'los que' and 'las que' mean 'that', 'which' or 'who' and often
  appear after a preposition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26133-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'El que', 'la que', 'los que' and 'las que' agree in gender and number with the
  noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26133-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'El cual', 'la cual', 'los cuales' and 'las cuales' mean 'that', 'which' or 'who'
  and often appear after a preposition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26133-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'El cual', 'la cual', 'los cuales' and 'las cuales' agree in gender and number with
  the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596123Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26133-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'El cual' tends to appear in more formal contexts than 'el que'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26087-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The negatives 'nada', 'nunca', 'nadie' and 'ninguno' can be used before a verb, or
  after as part of a double negative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597029Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26087-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To mean 'you' in an informal context, use 'tú'. In a formal context, use
  'usted'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26087-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is common to address unfamiliar as people 'usted', for example in commercial
  settings like a shop or restaurant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26087-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The plural form of 'usted' is 'ustedes'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26087-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'usted' and 'ustedes' respectively take the 3rd person singular and plural forms of
  the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26068-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to establish the tense of Spanish verbs in order to accurately
  translate them into English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26068-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When producing extended writing, you must establish the time frame of bullet point
  prompts to plan appropriate answers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26068-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet
  points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26155-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Manipulating present, past and future verbs allows you to tell a story and describe
  events clearly and accurately."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599613Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26155-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Being able to switch between tenses helps to make your writing and speaking more
  interesting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599618Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26155-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo, use the acronym PALM. It stands for People, Action,
  Location, Mood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26155-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is helpful to predict follow-up questions on a theme for developing conversation
  after describing a photo."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26021-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Stem-changing verbs like 'pedir', 'querer' and 'poder' have a spelling change in
  singular persons and 3rd person plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26021-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Present '-ER' verbs in 1st, 2nd and 3rd person plural have the ending -emos, -éis,
  -en."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26021-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns replace the receiver of the action of the verb, when the
  meaning is 'to me', 'for you'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26021-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'me' if the person affected by the verb is 'me', 'te' if it's you and 'le' if
  it's him, her or it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602114Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26021-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Spanish sentences can start with the subject or with the object."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26191-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You should answer role-play prompts with a short phrase or sentence. Do not add
  unnecessary detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602273Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26191-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a firm understanding of sound-spelling correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26191-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use the PALM acronym to structure photo descriptions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26191-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the conversation following the photo description, you should aim to develop
  answers using at least 3 verb clauses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26053-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When approaching reading aloud tasks, identify tricky sounds in the text before
  reading it aloud."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26053-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When preparing role-play answers, it is important to include a verb in each
  answer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602297Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26053-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating from Spanish to English, read the Spanish sentences carefully
  before translating."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602301Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26012-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regular -er/-ir verbs: 1st, 2nd, 3rd person singular PAST preterite (-í, iste &
  -ió)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26012-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some -er and -ir verbs whose stem ends in a vowel add an extra 'y' in 3rd person
  singular forms in the preterite tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606873Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26012-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When forming questions including a preposition, place the preposition at the
  beginning of the sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26060-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Possessive adjectives identify ownership of a noun, e.g. 'my', 'mine'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607452Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26060-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Possessive adjectives must agree with the nouns they describe in gender and
  number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607459Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26060-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The possessive adjectives 'mi', 'tu' and 'su' come before nouns. 'mío', 'tuyo' and
  'suyo' come after nouns for emphasis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607463Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26060-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Possessive pronouns replace nouns and identify ownership e.g. mine, yours."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607468Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26060-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The possessive pronouns 'el mío', 'el tuyo' and 'el suyo' have masculine, feminine,
  singular and plural forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607472Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26117-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Interesar'-type verbs express likes, emotions, interests - they work differently to
  normal Spanish verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607476Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26117-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Instead of saying 'I am interested in something', we say 'something interests me' -
  'me interesan estas aplicaciones.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607481Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26117-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Interesar'-type verbs agree with the subject, the ‘interesting thing(s)’; indirect
  object ‘me’ shows who is interested."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26117-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emphatic pronouns are used after prepositions such as 'a', 'para' 'sin', 'sobre',
  'con'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26117-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When used after 'a' before an 'interesar'-type verb, emphatic pronouns emphasise the
  person affected by the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607496Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26106-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Spanish definite articles are 'el', 'la', 'los' and 'las'. Indefinite articles are
  'un', 'una', 'unos' and 'unas'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26106-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Spanish differs from English in its use and non-use of articles in several ways."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607504Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26106-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Spanish requires the definite article with: general and abstract nouns, days of the
  week, titles and parts of the body."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607508Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26106-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Indefinite articles in Spanish can translate as 'a/an', 'one' or 'some'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607513Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26106-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Omit the indefinite article when referring to someone's profession in general, but
  include it when an adjective follows."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607517Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27617-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Working with a partner is a useful strategy for learning and consolidating
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27617-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to convey a range of
  information."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27617-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The PALM acronym is a useful prompt to include a range of information when
  describing photos."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26122-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect is used to give background information and for repeated actions in the
  past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26122-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The preterite tense is used to talk about completed actions in the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26120-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The perfect tense is used to express what has happened."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26120-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form conjugations of the perfect tense in Spanish, use the verb 'haber' + past
  participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26120-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the past participle of regular -ar verbs, remove the -ar and add -ado, and
  for -er/-ir verbs add -ido."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26120-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Common irregular past participles include 'dicho', 'muerto', 'roto', 'vuelto',
  'cubierto' and 'descubierto'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26035-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use ‘hacer’ in the 3rd person singular to talk about the weather."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26035-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Combining the preterite tense and the present tense is a useful way to contrast past
  and present experiences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26035-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to plan the use of tenses and the inclusion of regular and irregular
  verbs when creating a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26035-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Creating a checklist for range of language and another for accuracy can enhance the
  quality of extended writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26035-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Immediate repetition of a speaking task, with reduced support, improves
  performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26153-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of the most commonly-used Spanish verbs are irregular, e.g. 'ser', 'estar',
  'tener', 'hacer', 'venir', 'dar', 'ir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26153-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb 'dar' can be used to describe how something makes people feel. English uses
  'to be' + adjective for this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609600Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26153-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns ('me', 'te', 'le') are used with 'dar' + noun to say how
  something makes you and others feel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.609605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26029-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To say what time it is we say 'son las' followed by the number of the hour."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26029-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say that it’s a quarter past the hour, we use 'y cuarto'; to say that it's a
  quarter past the hour, we use 'y media'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26029-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To say that it’s a quarter to the hour, we use 'menos cuarto'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610205Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26029-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can use the simple present and the present continuous when making plans with
  friends."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26029-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Rosalía is a Spanish singer known for her genre-bending musical styles including
  Latin pop, flamenco and trap."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28484-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to convey a range of
  information."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611029Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28484-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The PALM acronym is a useful prompt to include a range of information when
  describing photos."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28484-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing photos in Spanish, it is important to use full sentences
  with verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28484-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make a photo description more interesting and complex, add justifications and
  contrasts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26100-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Identifying and avoiding distractors is key to ensuring we don't jump to the wrong
  conclusions during reading tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26100-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Active reading strategies support reading comprehension and accuracy in
  responses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611055Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26067-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A relative pronoun is a pronoun that introduces a relative clause."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26067-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A conjunction is a word that connects ideas between clauses in a sentence."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26067-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The word 'que' can be used as a relative pronoun or a conjunction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26067-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb stems of 'tener', 'hacer' and 'poder' in the inflectional future are
  'tendr-', 'har-' and 'podr-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611075Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26067-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can tell if an action is in the past, present or future by looking at the
  relevant verb ending."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611079Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28172-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The subjunctive expresses uncertainty, wishes, emotions or future possibilities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28172-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'cuando' + indicative if the action is regular or certain, and 'cuando' +
  subjunctive if the action is uncertain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28172-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After statements of fact or certainty use the indicative; after subjective points of
  view, use the subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28172-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wishing verbs ('querer', 'esperar', 'desear', 'preferir', 'necesitar') are followed
  by an infinitive or the subjunctive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28172-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use a verb of wishing + 'que' + subjunctive when you want someone else to do
  something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.611099Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29191-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the DOP 'lo' to mean 'him' or 'it' for masculine objects, and 'la' to mean 'her'
  or 'it' for feminine objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.616369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29191-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the DOP 'los' to mean 'them' for masculine objects, and 'las' to mean 'them' for
  feminine objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.616373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29191-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In 1-verb structures, direct object pronouns come before the verb."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.616377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29191-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 2-verb structures, direct object pronouns can come before the conjugated verb or
  attached to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.616381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29191-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When performing role-play, answers should be a short phrase or sentence. Do not add
  unnecessary detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.616385Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26099-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Spanish Civil War happened between 1936 and 1939. Franco became a dictator and
  ruled Spain until his death in 1975."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.617141Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26099-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect continuous is for ongoing past actions; form it with the imperfect of
  ‘estar’ and the present participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.617147Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26099-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the imperfect continuous, reflexive pronouns can go before the 1st verb or be
  attached after the present participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.617152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26099-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The preterite tense is used to talk about events completed in the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.617156Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26099-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When 'cuando' indicates an interruption to ongoing past actions, the preterite tense
  is generally used afterwards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.617160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26112-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reflexive verbs have the same subject and object."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618618Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26112-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural reflexive verbs, place the pronouns 'nos', 'os' and 'se' before
  verbs with the corresponding ending."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26112-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Possessive adjectives show who something belongs to and possessive pronouns replace
  possessive adjectives + nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26112-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The possessive adjectives 'mío', 'tuyo' and 'suyo' can follow 'ser' to show
  belonging to, e.g. 'la bolsa es mía'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26112-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form possessive pronouns, use the definite article before 'mío', 'suyo' or
  'tuyo', based on gender and number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26105-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs such as 'me, te, le gustaría' and 'quisiera' can be used to discuss
  future desires."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618642Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26105-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The conditional is a verb form used to express what would happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618646Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26105-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate singular forms of the conditional for regular verbs, add -ía, -ías, -ía
  to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618650Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26010-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[gue] sounds like 'llegué', [ge] sounds like 'gente'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618654Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26010-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regular -ar verbs: 1st, 2nd, 3rd person singular PAST preterite (-é, -aste &
  -ó)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618661Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26010-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Subject pronouns yo, tú, él, ella; we usually omit the use of subject pronoun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26010-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are some contexts where the use of subject pronouns is appropriate"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26088-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To mean 'your' when addressing 'tú', use 'tu'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26088-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To mean 'your' when addressing 'usted', use 'su'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618678Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26088-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'tu' and 'su' are possessive adjectives."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618682Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26088-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'tu' and 'su' become 'tus' and 'sus' when describing the ownership of plural
  nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618686Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26061-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[ge] is pronounced as in 'gente', [gi] is pronounced as in 'imaginar' and [j] is
  pronounced as in 'ojo'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618690Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26061-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Demonstrative adjectives indicate a particular noun and they must agree with this
  noun in gender and number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26061-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjectives ending in -z, -e, and -ista have have the plural endings -ces, -es and
  -istas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26061-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'el mejor', 'el peor', 'el mayor' and 'el menor' are common irregular
  superlatives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26061-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Superlatives must agree with the nouns they describe in gender and number."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618710Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26044-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All nouns in Spanish have grammatical gender. They are either masculine or
  feminine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26044-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Masculine nouns ending in -o change to -a in the feminine form."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620090Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26044-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nouns ending in -ista, -ente and -ante don’t change spelling in the feminine
  form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26071-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Identifying sound-spelling links can help you with listening and reading in Spanish
  and completing dictation tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26071-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sound-spelling correspondence [que] sounds like 'porque' and [qui] like
  'equipo'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26071-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If Spanish words ending in -n, -s or a vowel have final-syllable stress an accent on
  the final vowel shows this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26071-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can form answers to questions in Spanish by converting 2nd person language into
  1st person language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620122Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26125-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When preparing and performing role-plays, it’s important to include a verb in each
  answer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26125-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Questions in some role-plays may be addressed to 'usted' and therefore use language
  in the third person singular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26125-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Opinions about shopping can be developed by giving justifications and contrasts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26125-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Conjunctions can provide justifications and connectives can provide contrasts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620139Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26050-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Present-tense verbs ending in -gir or -ger have a spelling change in the 1st person
  singular e.g. dirigir > dirijo."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26050-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[gi] and [ge] are pronounced as in ‘imaginar’ and ‘gente’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620322Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26050-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[j] is pronounced as in 'ojo'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26050-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You can use context, cognates and prior learning to aid reading comprehension."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26050-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Before translating from English into Spanish, it is important to consider the
  grammatical features involved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620339Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26078-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used to talk about habitual actions in the past or to
  describe how things were in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26078-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The regular imperfect endings for singular -ar verbs are -aba, -abas and -aba."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621304Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26078-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The regular imperfect endings for singular -er/-ir verbs are -ía, -ías and -ía."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26078-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ser' is irregular in the imperfect tense. Use 'era' or 'eras' to mean was/were +
  trait."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621313Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28174-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use the affirmative imperative (a positive command) to tell somebody to do
  something or give instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28174-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For -ar verbs the ending is -a, and for -er and -ir verbs the ending is -e."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28174-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs express ideas like advice, possibility, or obligation. They are most
  often followed by an infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28174-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some key modal verbs to give advice are 'tener que', 'deber' and 'poder'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621331Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26147-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The perfect tense is used to express what has happened."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26147-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate the perfect tense, use 'he', 'has', 'ha', 'hemos', 'habéis' or 'han'
  (from 'haber') + past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26147-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the past participle of regular verbs, remove the -ar/-er/-ar and add -ado
  (-ar verbs) or -ido (-er/-ir verbs)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26147-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Remember to use the correct ending to refer to the right person in the present
  tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26066-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The inflectional future tense is used to express what will happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26066-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the inflectional future tense of regular verbs in the singular, add the
  endings -é, -ás, -á to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29106-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the singular preterite persons of -er and -ir verbs, we take the infinitive,
  remove –er/-ir and add endings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29106-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The -er and -ir singular preterite endings are: -í (I), -iste (you), -ió (she, he,
  it)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29106-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In conversation it is important to listen carefully to and understand the tense of
  questions before answering."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621805Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29106-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Being able to ask questions in different tenses, as well as answer them, is key to
  successful communication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26083-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The verb 'hace' + noun describes a range of weather conditions, e.g. 'hace sol'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621814Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26083-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The verb 'hay' means 'there is' or 'there are'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26083-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say you have been doing something for a period of time, you can use 'present
  tense verb + desde hace + time period'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621824Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26083-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say you have been doing something for a period of time, you can use 'llevo + time
  period + present participle'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26083-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28175-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Leitner System is a simple but very powerful method to revise vocabulary."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28175-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To talk about a completed action in the past we use the preterite."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28175-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Decir’, ‘estar’, ‘venir’, ‘poner’, ‘querer’, ‘dar’, ‘traer’ and ‘poder’ have
  irregular stems in the preterite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28175-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28170-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The subjunctive indicates uncertainty, wishing or possibility, or refers to actions
  that have not yet happened."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28170-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Subjunctive verb forms include: 'ser' → 'sea', 'tener' → 'tenga', 'hacer' →
  'haga'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28170-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, the subjunctive is also used after subjective points of view, e.g. 'es
  importante que', 'es esencial que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623123Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28170-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The subjunctive is used after 'que' when the action is uncertain, desired, or not a
  fact."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28170-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the verb before 'que' expresses certainty or a statement of fact, an indicative
  verb follows 'que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28169-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Successful transcription involves careful listening, writing, and checking, ensuring
  every word written makes sense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28169-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Pre-listening strategies are important to help you prepare to listen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28169-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During-listening strategies help you stay focused, understand key information, and
  process what you hear in real time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28169-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Post-listening strategies help you check your understanding and reflect on the
  content."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.623150Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28483-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is important to respond to role-play prompts with a short phrase or sentence."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.624726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28483-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Interrogatives can be used to ask questions in a role-play scenario."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.624731Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28483-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Useful interrogatives in Spanish are: '¿cuándo?', '¿cómo?', '¿dónde?', '¿cuánto?',
  '¿qué?' and '¿hay?'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.624753Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26091-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to revisit and practise vocabulary regularly to store it in your
  long-term memory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26091-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the affirmative imperative to tell somebody to do something or to give
  instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26091-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperative forms of 'ser', 'ir', 'tener' and 'venir' are irregular: 'sé', 've',
  'ten' and 'ven'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26091-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct and indirect object pronouns follow and are attached to affirmative
  imperative verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28173-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The subjunctive expresses uncertainty, wishes, emotions or future possibilities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28173-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Subjunctive verb forms include: 'ser' → 'sea', 'tener' → 'tenga', 'hacer' → 'haga'
  and 'ir' → 'vaya'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28173-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Querer', 'pedir', 'decir', 'insistir', 'recomendar', and 'sugerir' are verbs of
  command and request."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28173-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use a verb of command/request + 'que' + subjunctive when you want someone else to do
  something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28173-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When one person is doing the action, verbs of command/request are followed by an
  infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26108-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate singular forms of the conditional, add -ía, -ías, -ía to the
  infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26108-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Habría’, ‘haría’, ‘podría’, ‘pondría’ and ‘tendría’ are common irregular
  conditional verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26108-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of the conditional, add -íamos, -íais, -ían to the
  infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631844Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26108-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verbs ‘decir’, ‘querer’, ‘saber’, ‘salir’ and ‘venir’ have irregular stems in
  the conditional."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26132-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Decir', 'estar', 'venir', 'poner', 'querer', 'saber', 'traer' and 'poder' have
  irregular stems in the preterite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26132-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Relative pronouns are words that introduce a relative clause, giving more
  information about a noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26132-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The relative pronoun 'que' means 'who, that, which', 'donde' means 'where' and
  'cuando' means 'when'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631887Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26132-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unlike question words, relative pronouns in Spanish do not have a written
  accent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27620-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used for what used to happen repeatedly and to set the scene
  in past-tense accounts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27620-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The past continuous tense is used for what was happening and to set the scene in
  past-tense accounts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27620-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The preterite tense is used for something completed in the past and to drive the
  narrative in past-tense accounts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27620-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is important to make a plan before producing an extended piece of writing."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26089-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When preparing and performing role-plays, it is important to answer using short
  phrases or sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631916Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26089-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You must avoid giving one-word answers in role-plays."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26089-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Role-play answers must be kept brief. Overcomplicating answers runs the risk of
  introducing ambiguity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26089-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to be aware of different forms of address, 'tú' and 'usted', when
  preparing and performing role-plays."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631929Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26041-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When approaching read aloud tasks, take time to identify and mentally rehearse key
  sounds first."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631975Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26041-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating from Spanish to English, read the Spanish sentences carefully
  before translating."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.631979Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26079-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using knowledge of vocabulary and grammar is a useful strategy for completing
  gap-fill tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633073Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26079-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The perfect tense is used to express what has happened, e.g. 'I have gone'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26079-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the perfect tense, use 'he', 'has', 'ha', 'hemos', 'habéis' or 'han' (from
  'haber') + past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633084Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26079-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To form the past participle of regular -ar verbs, remove the -ar and add -ado."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26079-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the past participle of regular -er and -ir verbs, remove the -er/-ir and add
  -ido."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26123-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Ese’, 'esa', 'aquel' and 'aquella' all mean 'that' before a singular or uncountable
  noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633100Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26123-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "‘Esos’, 'esas', 'aquellos' and 'aquellas' all mean 'those' before a plural noun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633104Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26123-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Aquel', 'aquella', 'aquellos' and 'aquellas' refer to something far away in space
  or time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26123-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Spanish demonstrative adjectives agree in gender with the noun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26111-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of -ar verbs in the simple present, remove the -ar and add
  -amos, -áis, -an."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633613Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26111-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To conjugate plural forms of -ar verbs in the preterite, remove the -ar and add
  -amos, -asteis, -aron."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633618Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26111-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verb endings and time markers can help us to distinguish between past and present
  time frames in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27615-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'iba', 'ibas' and 'iba' are the 1st, 2nd and 3rd person singular imperfect forms of
  'ir'. These are irregular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633626Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27615-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The preterite tense is used to talk about something completed in the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27615-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used to talk about something that used to happen repeatedly
  in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27615-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The past continuous is created by combining imperfect forms of 'estar' with the
  present participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27615-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When 'cuando' indicates an interruption to a past continuous action, the preterite
  tense is generally used afterwards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26113-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[gu] is pronounced as in 'preguntar' and [j] is pronounced as in 'ojo'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26113-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Words ending in a vowel, -n or -s have penultimate syllable stress unless they have
  an accent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26113-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Words ending in a consonant other than -n or -s have final syllable stress unless
  they have an accent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26113-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plural reflexive verbs can express a reciprocal action when people are doing the
  action to each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633684Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26081-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Impersonal verbs don’t refer to a particular person or thing."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633692Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26081-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Common impersonal verb phrases in Spanish are 'hay que', 'se puede', 'se necesita'
  and 'se debe'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26081-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make suggestions to someone, use 'hay que', 'se puede', 'se necesita' or 'se
  debe' followed by an infinitive verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633700Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26081-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Passive sentences focus on what is done rather than who does it."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26081-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spanish, passive sentences can be formed using reflexive pronoun 'se' + 3rd
  person singular or plural verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633709Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28481-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When preparing answers to role-plays, it's important to answer using short phrases
  or sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634159Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28481-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You must avoid giving one-word answers in role-plays."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634163Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28481-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Role-play answers must be kept brief. Overcomplicating answers runs the risk of
  introducing ambiguity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28481-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a role-play, you are likely to be addressed as 'usted'. As such, questions will
  contain 3rd person language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26040-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When followed by a noun, 'para' translates as 'for' or 'to'; when followed by an
  infinitive, it means '(in order) to'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26040-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sin (without) can also be followed by nouns or an infinitive, with the meaning
  'without -ing'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634296Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26040-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Antes de + infinitive' means 'before + -ing' and 'después de + infinitive' means
  'after + -ing'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26040-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Infinitive clauses help you create longer sentences and extend your writing."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634304Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26040-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using a variety of subjects is an easy way to give more detail and develop your
  sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27619-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1st, 2nd and 3rd person plural imperfect endings of regular -er and -ir verbs
  are -íamos, -íais and -ían."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634312Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27619-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1st, 2nd and 3rd person plural imperfect forms of ‘ver’ are ‘veíamos’, ‘veíais’
  and ‘veían’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27619-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1st, 2nd and 3rd person singular imperfect endings of regular -ar verbs are
  -aba, -abas and -aba."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27619-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1st, 2nd and 3rd person singular imperfect endings of regular -er and -ir verbs
  are -ía, -ías, and -ía."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27619-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regular preterite tense endings are: -é, -aste, -ó for -ar verbs; and -í, -iste, -ió
  for -er and -ir verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634333Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26018-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Present tense -er/-ir verbs in 1st, 2nd, 3rd person singular (-o, -es, -e)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26018-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs that end in –cer or –cir that have a spelling change in the 1st person
  singular. We add a 'z' before the 'co'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634341Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26018-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Direct object pronouns (lo, la, los, las) come before the verb."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634345Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26018-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'lo' to mean 'him' or 'it' (for masculine objects) and 'la' to mean 'her' or
  'it' (for feminine objects)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26018-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'los' to mean 'them' (for masculine objects) and 'las' to mean 'them' (for
  feminine objects)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634353Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26146-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[ce], [ci] and [z] sound like the 'th' in 'think' in most of Spain, and 's' in Latin
  America and the Canary Islands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26146-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[h] is silent at the beginning of a word or in between vowels. [ch] is pronounced
  like 'noche'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634747Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26146-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It’s important to identify tricky sounds before attempting read aloud tasks."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26146-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When preparing and performing role-plays, it is important to answer using short
  phrases or sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26146-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The question you ask must be relevant to the context of the role-play."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26017-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The indefinite adjective 'alguno' is used to say 'some' and it goes before the noun
  it describes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26017-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In statements, use 'algún' before a masculine singular noun and 'alguna' before a
  feminine singular noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26017-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In statements, use 'algunos' before masculine plural nouns and 'algunas' before
  feminine plural nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.634774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26115-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Possessive adjectives show who something belongs to."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26115-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Mío', 'tuyo', 'suyo', 'nuestro' and 'vuestro' are possessive adjectives in Spanish
  and can be used after 'ser'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26115-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Possessive pronouns replace a possessive adjective and a noun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26115-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'El mío', 'el tuyo', 'el suyo', 'el nuestro' and 'el vuestro' are possessive
  pronouns in Spanish."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636187Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26115-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Possessive adjectives and pronouns change to reflect the grammatical gender and
  number of the thing possessed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26158-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26158-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The VAN check involves checking your verbs, adjectives and nouns after writing."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26158-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The VAN check can significantly improve accuracy when completing writing tasks."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26158-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You must respond to the bullet point using the correct tense (e.g. past, present,
  future) to fully address it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636208Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26129-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the affirmative imperative to tell somebody to do something or to give
  instructions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636212Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26129-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to somebody familiar to you ('tú') with the affirmative imperative of
  an -ar verb, use the ending -a."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26129-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When talking to somebody familiar to you ('tú') with the affirmative imperative of
  an -er/-ir verb, use the ending -e."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26129-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Irregular imperative verbs include: 'sé', 've', 'ten', 'ven', 'haz', 'di', 'pon',
  'sal'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636224Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26129-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form the familiar affirmative imperative of reflexive verbs, add the pronoun 'te'
  along with any necessary accents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26020-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Adjectives need to agree in gender and number with the noun that they describe."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26020-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Mismo', 'último', 'propio', 'primero', 'segundo' and 'tercer' are examples of
  prenominal adjectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636240Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26020-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some prenominal adjectives lose the –o ending before a singular masculine noun:
  primer, tercer, buen, mal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26020-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The position of adjectives changes its meaning. This happens with 'grande', 'único',
  'pobre' and 'viejo'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.636249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

